    "url": "https://hdl.handle.net/10419%2F214088",
    "title": "EconStor: Filter bubble",
    "content": "Skip navigation A service of the zbw EconStor Alexander von Humboldt Institut für Internet und Gesellschaft (HIIG), Berlin Internet Policy Review: Journal on Internet Regulation, Alexander von Humboldt Institute for Internet and Society Please use this identifier to cite or link to this item: https://hdl.handle.net/10419/214088 copy to clipboard Title: Filter bubble Authors: Bruns, Axel Year of Publication: 2019 Citation: [Journal:] Internet Policy Review [ISSN:] 2197-6775 [Volume:] 8 [Issue:] 4 [Publisher:] Alexander von Humboldt Institute for Internet and Society [Place:] Berlin [Year:] 2019 [Pages:] 1-14 Publisher: Alexander von Humboldt Institute for Internet and Society, Berlin Abstract: Introduced by tech entrepreneur and activist Eli Pariser in 2011, the \u0027filter bubble\u0027 is a persistent concept which suggests that search engines and social media, together with their recommendation and personalisation algorithms, are centrally culpable for the societal and ideological polarisation experienced in many countries: we no longer encounter a balanced and healthy information diet, but only see information that targets our established interests and reinforces our existing worldviews. Filter bubbles are seen as critical enablers of Brexit, Trump, Bolsonaro, and other populist political phenomena, and search and social media companies have been criticised for failing to prevent their development. Yet, there is scant empirical evidence for their existence, or for the related concept of \u0027echo chambers\u0027: indeed, search and social media users generally appear to encounter a highly centrist media diet that is, if anything, more diverse than that of non-users. However, the persistent use of these concepts in mainstream media and political debates has now created its own discursive reality that continues to impact materially on societal institutions, media and communication platforms, and ordinary users themselves. This article provides a critical review of the \u0027filter bubble\u0027 idea, and concludes that its persistence has served only to redirect scholarly attention from far more critical areas of enquiry. Subjects: Filter bubble Echo chambers Social media Social network Polarisation Persistent Identifier of the first edition: doi:10.14763/2019.4.1426 Creative Commons License: Document Type: Article Appears in Collections: Internet Policy Review: Journal on Internet Regulation, Alexander von Humboldt Institute for Internet and Society Files in This Item: File Description Size Format IntPolRev-2019-4-1426.pdf download file 224.12 kB Adobe PDF Download Statistics BibTeX-Export Items in EconStor are protected by copyright, with all rights reserved, unless otherwise indicated.",
